Next, determine the smallest $ n \geq 3 $ such that concatenating $ 2^{10}, 2^{20}, \ldots, 2^{10n} $ results in $ A \equiv 2^{10n} \pmod{2^{170}} $. The key is ensuring all terms before $ 2^{10n} $ in the concatenation are divisible by $ 2^{170} $. For the $ j $-th term (before the last), the exponent of 2 is $ 10j + \sum_{m=j+1}^n d_m $, where $ d_m $ is the number of decimal digits of $ 2^{10m} $.

Using $ d_m = \lfloor 10m \log_{10} 2 \rfloor + 1 \approx 3m + 1 $, the critical term (smallest exponent) is for $ j = n-1 $, giving exponent $ 13n - 9 $. Solving $ 13n - 9 \geq 170 $ yields $ n \geq 14 $. Verifying, $ n = 14 $ ensures all exponents are $ \geq 170 $, while $ n = 13 $ fails (exponent 160). Thus, the smallest $ n $ is 14.",
